<HL>
   Eagle-Picher Expects
   Asbestos-Claim Costs
   To Hit $110 Million
</HL>
<DATE>
06/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   EPI
</CO>
<IN>
BUILDING MATERIALS (BLD)
EARNINGS (ERN)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   CINCINNATI -- Eagle-Picher Industries Inc. said that costs
related to asbestos claims are expected to total about $110
million this year and that it's concerned about a sudden
upturn in the number of such claims being filed.
   The industrial company also reported that in its second
quarter ended May 31 net rose 74% to $22.6 million, or $2.11
a share, from $13 million, or $1.22 a share, a year earlier.
The latest quarter included a gain of $11.9 million, or $1.11
a share, from the sale of a division.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sales slid about 5% to $184.4 million from $193.1 million.
   But despite improvements in operations, especially those
businesses serving the automotive industry, the company said
its asbestos litigation costs remains a "serious problem."
   Until the second quarter, the number of new claims had
been decreasing, a trend that the company had expected to
continue. But in the quarter, about 6,200 new claims were
received compared with 4,000 a year earlier and 4,900 in the
1987 quarter, the company said.
   In the quarter, the company said it disposed of 3,600
claims, compared with 3,400 a year earlier and 1,500 in the
1988 second quarter. Total costs related to those settlements
were about $31 million for the quarter and $62 million for
the six months.
   To fund litigation costs, the company has said it intends
to sell off additional assets, including its trim division
and injection-molding division, which make rubber molded
parts and trim for the automotive industry. "In order to
avoid a severe liquidity problem, the company must complete
the sale of these assets on a timely basis," the company
said.
   The company is a defendant in about 62,100 claims stemming
from its manufacture, from 1934 until 1971, of an
asbestos-containing insulating cement used principally in
shipbuilding and refinery construction.
</TEXT>
