<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Fear of Inflation
   Just Doesn't Fly
</HL>
<DATE>
06/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15
</SO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   Both Lawrence A. Kudlow ("What's Good for America Is Good
for Bonds," May 9) and Irving Kristol ("Inflation: Almost
Never What It Seems," May 16) are right in their
editorial-page articles to observe that the conduct of Alan
Greenspan's Fed offers no grounds to fear inflation. Yet
there is even more evidence:
   -- The price of gold has not simply been steady, it has
fallen to below $375 per ounce. If anything, this measure
indicates a slight tightening; 1980s markets were healthy and
inflation low with gold at $425 to $475.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   -- Exchange rates have exhibited less volatility than at
any time since 1973, thanks to both Mr. Greenspan and former
Treasury Secretary James Baker's G-7 initiative, causing at
least one Journal article to remark they have now become
almost "boring." While exchange rates are not the best
barometer -- it is possible to have global inflation or
deflation with steady exchange rates -- some analysts watch
them closely, and they certainly point to no inflation.
   Even the money supply, rightly understood, reinforces the
case. To find a meaningful monetary aggregate we must exclude
currency outstanding -- much of which may be finding its way
into East European and other countries where dollars are the
"de facto" money. We have this in the Fed's statistics on
non-borrowed reserves, an aggregate that, unlike M-1 through
M-3 and even the monetary base, excludes the potentially
misleading currency.
   Non-borrowed reserve growth under Mr. Greenspan: 0.5%
since taking office. In fact, reserves stood at $58.4 billion
in August 1987; at $58.4 billion in January 1988; at $58.7
billion in January 1989; and $58.7 billion in May 1990. Thus,
interest rates of 8.5% on bonds become hard to explain in
terms of legitimate inflation fears. Either the market is
ill-informed or it simply doubts the Fed will stay the course
set by Messrs. Baker and Greenspan.
   The remedy for the former is for bond buyers to wake up
and take advantage of still-high rates. The remedy for the
latter is for the Fed and current Treasury Secretary Nicholas
Brady to institutionalize all this price stability, gaining
what Fed Gov. Wayne Angell has rightly called the critical
"announcement effect." Monetary authorities already have done
the difficult part of establishing a commodity-backed dollar.
Why not the easy part?
   Gregory Fossedal
   Chairman
   Bruce Thompson
   Treasurer
   Alexis de Tocqueville Institution
   Stanford, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900620-0115
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900620-0115.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Leibler Resigning
   As Amex President
   To Join an Insurer
   ----
   By William Power
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8
</SO>
<CO>
   WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Kenneth R. Leibler, president of the American
Stock Exchange for the past 4 1/2 years and one of the
best-knownfigures in the securities industry, is leaving the
Amex for a top job at Liberty Financial Cos. in Boston.
   Mr. Leibler, 41 years old, was passed over last October
when the stock exchange brought in former Congressman James
R. Jones to succeed longtime chairman Arthur Levitt Jr.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Leibler will assume the new position of president and
chief operating officer at Liberty Financial, a unit of
Liberty Mutual Insurance Co. Among the eight Liberty
Financial operating companies he'll run are Stein Roe &amp;
Farnham and Liberty Asset Management moneymanagement
companies, with combined assets under management of $15
billion, and the insurer Keystone Provident Life. Mr. Leibler
will report to Sam Marinella, chief executive officer of
Liberty Financial.
   Mr. Jones said Mr. Leibler's departure -- which apparently
caught the Amex by surprise -- is a "big loss" for the
exchange, which is a tiny stock market compared with the New
York Stock Exchange, but which has become one of the
country's major options markets. Mr. Jones said no decision
has been made about a successor or about whether a search
committee will be formed.
   The youngest president of a securities exchange when he
took over as Amex president in 1986, Mr. Leibler has worked
at the Amex for most of his career, starting with an
entry-level job in the options division 15 years ago. Joseph
Hardiman, president of the National Association of Securities
Dealers, praised him yesterday for his knowledge of markets.
   For his part, Mr. Leibler said yesterday that he is
looking forward to the "much broader management capacity" of
his new job. "There's no doubt that when I got to this
position at age 36, this wasn't something I would do for the
next 30 years."
   He hopes the move allows him the chance for a short
vacation to indulge in his "two major passions" -- vegetable
gardening and collecting wine. He also has a passion for
business, of course. One day, "I hope to get a vineyard and
combine them all," Mr. Leibler said.
   It has been an active time in the executive suites of
major exchanges. The New York Stock Exchange's chairman, John
J. Phelan Jr., also plans to step down later this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
