<HL>
   New Securities Issues
</HL>
<DATE>
06/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C17
</SO>
<CO>
   STPL FNM MER FNB NOB AFRIC EUROP J.NTT JAPNY G.DAI FREST
J.DKD J.KAY
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
</IN>
<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report:
                                                                                                       

                        CORPORATES
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   St. Paul Cos. -- $100 million of 9 3/8% non-callable
notes, due June 15, 1997, was priced at 99.918 to yield
9.39%. The issue was priced at a spread of 0.85 percentage
point above the Treasury's seven-year note. Rated double-A-2
by Moody's Investors Service Inc. and double-A by Standard &amp;
Poor's Corp., the issue will be sold through underwriters led
by Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co.
   Potomac Edison Co. -- $80 million of first mortgage bonds,
due June 1, 2020, was won through competitive bidding by a
group led by Goldman Sachs and will be reoffered with a
coupon of 9 5/8% at 99.15 to yield 9.71%. The bonds, which
are non-refundable for five years, were priced at a spread of
1.23 percentage points above the Treasury's 30-year bond.
Goldman won the issue with a bid of 98.716 for a 9 5/8%
coupon that resulted in a net interest cost to the company of
9.757%. The issue is rated double-A-3 by Moody's and
double-A-minus by S&amp;P.
                                                                                                       

                        MUNICIPALS
                                                                                                       

   Los Angeles County -- $1.1 billion of tax and revenue
anticipation notes, due July 1, 1991, were tentatively priced
by a Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. group to yield 5.80% in 1991. The
6.25% notes are rated MIG-1 by Moody's and SP1-Plus by S&amp;P.
   Minnesota -- $200 million of general obligation bonds, due
Aug. 1, 1991-2009, apparently were won by a First Boston
Corp. group with a bid setting the true interest cost at
6.90%. The bonds, rated double-A by Moody's and double-A-plus
by S&amp;P, were priced for reoffering to yield from 5.75% in
1991 to 7.05% in 2008 and 2009. There are no term bonds.
   Pennsylvania Higher Education Facilities Authority --
$58.8 million of state system of higher education revenue
bonds, Series D, due June 15, 1991-2007, and 2015, apparently
were won by a Chase Securities Inc. group with a bid setting
the true interest cost at 7.19112%. The bonds, insured and
rated triple-A by Moody's and S&amp;P were priced for reoffering
to yield from 5.90% in 1991 to 7.24% in 2015. Current
interest serial bonds are priced to yield from 5.90% in 1991
to 7.15% in 2007. There are $23.3 million of 7.15% term bonds
priced at 99 to yield 7.24% in 2015.
                                                                                                       

                         MORTGAGE
                                                                                                       

   Federal National Mortgage Association -- $300 million of
real estate mortgage investment conduit securities is being
offered in 11 classes by Salomon Brothers Inc. The offering,
Series 1990-83, is backed by Fannie Mae 10% securities.
Price, yield and spread information weren't immediately
available.
   Merrill Lynch Mortgage Investors -- $94.6 million of
Series A Remic pass-through certificates backed by
manufactured housing loans with a coupon rate of 9.70% at 99
20/32 to yield 9.897% through Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
The issue, MLMI 1990-D, was priced at a spread of 1.43
percentage points over the Treasury's five-year note. The
underlying loans are being sold by Green Tree Acceptance Inc.
There is a 4.82-year average life. The issue is rated
double-A-2 by Moody's, based on the quality of the underlying
loans and a subordinated class of $23.7 million, which
absorbs losses on the senior securities.
                                                                                                       

                       ASSET-BACKED
                                                                                                       

   First Chicago Corp. -- $1 billion of securities backed by
credit-card loans with a coupon rate of 9 1/4% at 99.91 to
yield 9.271% in a global offering through First Boston and
Credit Suisse First Boston Ltd. The securities yield 0.80
percentage point over five-year U.S. Treasury notes. The
issue, First Chicago Master Trust II, Series 1990-A, has a
legal maturity of Dec. 15, 1996, and an expected maturity of
July 15, 1995. There will be a one-time principal payment
June 15, 1995. First interest payment will be Dec. 17, 1990.
The securities are expected to be rated triple-A by Moody's
and S&amp;P, based on the quality of the underlying credit-card
loans and a letter of credit covering 12% of the deal from
Credit Suisse. The originator and servicer of the credit-card
loans underlying the deal is FCC National Bank, a unit of
First Chicago Corp.
   Norwest Corp. -- $400 million of securities backed by
credit-card loans with a coupon rate of 9.15% at 99.975 to
yield 9.21% through Morgan Stanley. Norwest Investor Services
Inc. is co-manager. The issue, Norwest Master Trust Series A,
was priced at a spread of 0.75 percentage point over the
interpolated three-year and four-year Treasury notes.
Servicer of the credit-card loans underlying the issue is
Norwest Bank Iowa. The issue has a 3.5-year average life.
Legal maturity is Dec. 15, 1995, and expected maturity is
June 15, 1994. The first interest payment will be made on
July 16. Interest only will be paid in the first three years.
The first principal payment will be July 15, 1993. The issue
is expected to be rated triple-A by Moody's and S&amp;P, based on
the quality of the underlying credit-card loans and a letter
of credit covering 12% of the deal from Union Bank of
Switzerland.
                                                                                                       

