<HL>
   Thomas Industries
   Says 2nd-Quarter Net
   Will Fall 20% to 30%
</HL>
<DATE>
06/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   TII
</CO>
<LP>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. -- Thomas Industries Inc., citing softer
than expected U.S. residential and commercial construction,
said it expects second-quarter profit to fall 20% to 30% from
43 cents a share a year earlier.
   But the producer of lighting products, compressors and
pumps said sales are expected to top the year-earlier $112.5
million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Thomas said that the second-half outlook is uncertain but
that earnings for the year are expected to meet or exceed
1989 levels, adjusted for non-recurring gains.
   In 1989, Thomas earned $20.6 million, or $2.02 a share, on
sales of $436.6 million. Included were non-recurring gains of
$7.4 million, or 75 cents a share.
   In addition to the U.S. construction slowdown, Thomas said
it has been hurt by a construction trade strike in Canada
that has weakened demand for its lighting products. Also, it
said, it has been hurt by strong competitive pricing
pressures.
   However, the company said it has been increasing its
lighting sales and market share. It added that the compressor
and pump markets are buffering it somewhat from the cyclical
swings in the construction industry.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
Thomas closed at $17, down $1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900620-0047
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900620-0047.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Judge Ends `Minitrial'
   In Keating's Bid for S&amp;L
</HL>
<DATE>
06/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16
</SO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Federal Judge Stanley Sporkin concluded an
unusual "minitrial" in Charles Keating's suit to recover
Lincoln Savings &amp; Loan Association, saying, "It's up to me,
and I'm going to ponder it."
   After 30 days of testimony that looked at a small sample
of Lincoln's real estate developments and securities
investments, Judge Sporkin has three choices: He can uphold
the government's April 1989 seizure of the thrift, return the
thrift or order a full trial.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The government and Mr. Keating remained fiercely at odds
yesterday as final arguments were heard over Mr. Keating's
suit challenging the takeover. Lincoln was the principal
subsidiary of Phoenix, Ariz.-based American Continental
Corp., of which Mr. Keating is chairman.
   Mr. Keating charged that incompetent regulators carried
out a "vendetta" against him and smothered Lincoln with
unfair regulation because it didn't operate like a
traditional thrift. The government says Mr. Keating and his
business colleagues crafted sham transactions that allowed
them to drain tens of millions of dollars from Lincoln that
was paid to American Continental and then to Mr. Keating and
his associates in salaries and dividends.
   Mr. Sporkin didn't indicate when he plans to make a
decision in the case.
</TEXT>
