<HL>
   CD Yields at Banks
   And Brokerage Firms
   Fell Slightly for Week
</HL>
<DATE>
06/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C21
</SO>
<IN>
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Yields on certificates of deposit at major
banks and brokerage firms fell slighly in the week that ended
yesterday.
   Average yields on small-denomination CDs sold directly by
banks were flat to down slightly. The average yield on a
one-year consumer CD eased to 7.85% from 7.87%, while the
five-year CD average dipped to 8.09% from 8.11%, according to
an 18-bank survey by Banxquote Money Markets, an information
service here.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   While none of the banks in the survey offered a yield as
high as 9%, investors can still find consumer CDs at some
banks that yield that much or more.
   Average yields on small-denomination CDs sold by leading
broker dealers were mixed. The average yield on six-month CDs
slipped to 8.17% from 8.27%, while the average for two-year
CDs remained at 8.30%, according to Banxquote.
   Meanwhile, average yields for large-denomination CDs,
which typically require deposits of $90,000 or more, were
down slightly. The average yield on one-year jumbo CDs dipped
to 7.90% from 7.98%, while five-year maturities eased to
8.22% from 8.25%.
   "Because banks are now reducing their loan portfolios,
they are not hungry for cash in order to make new loans.
That's why they can afford to lower their CD rates," said
Norberto Mehl, chairman of Banxquote. He said he expects the
pattern to continue for the foreseeable future.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900620-0037
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900620-0037.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Coca-Cola Enterprises
   Faces $1 Million Fine
   In Unit's Conviction
</HL>
<DATE>
06/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   CCE KO
</CO>
<IN>
BEVERAGES (BVG)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   ATLANTA -- Coca-Cola Enterprises Inc. said it could face a
fine of as much as $1 million following a conviction on
conspiracy and bribery charges related to the sale of Coke to
a U.S. Navy base.
   In February, the Justice Department issued an 11-count
indictment against a Coca-Cola bottling unit, Mid-Atlantic
Coca-Cola Bottling Co., on charges related to the sale of
soft drinks at the Navy operations base in Norfolk, Va. The
indictment also charged that illegal gratuities were paid to
a former civilian U.S. Navy procurement officer.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Two weeks ago, a federal court in Norfolk found
Mid-Atlantic guilty of all 11 counts under the indictment. In
a Securities and Exchange Commission filing, Coca-Cola
Enterprises said it may appeal. Sentencing is set for Aug. 3.
   The indictment, covering sales in 1984 and 1985, also
named Michael A. Hedges, a former Mid-Atlantic area vice
president, sales, and James J. Valerio, a former Mid-Atlantic
area controller.
   Before the trial, Mr. Hedges pleaded guilty to two counts
of paying illegal gratuities, according to the SEC filing.
Mr. Valerio was acquitted of a charge of conspiracy, the
filing said. Mr. Hedges couldn't be reached for comment.
   Coca-Cola Enterprises, a bottling business formed in 1986,
is 49%-owned by Coca-Cola Co. Coca-Cola acquired a
controlling interest in Mid-Atlantic in September 1984,
subsequently turning over its ownership of the business to
Coca-Cola Enterprises.
   Coca-Cola officials couldn't be reached for comment.
</TEXT>
