<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
06/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   A NEW BUDGET PLAN is expected from a top Bush official in
an effort to jump-start stalled talks with Congress. Darman's
proposal reportedly includes deficit cuts of $45 billion to
$50 billion, including a stiff $17 billion reduction in
"entitlement" allocations. Democrats are likely to oppose the
plan because it relies mostly on lowering domestic spending.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   RJR Nabisco started a $5.3 billion refinancing effort that
will drastically reshape its balance sheet. The proposal,
backed by main shareholder KKR, reportedly seeks to retire
more than $4 billion of the food and tobacco firm's
poorest-performing junk bonds.
   ---
   Housing starts sank 1.4% in May to their lowest level
since 1982, in a further sign of a sluggish economy. The
apartment market was the hardest hit.
   ---
   Stock prices rebounded slightly while the bond market
drifted lower. The Dow Jones industrials rose 11.38 points to
2893.56. The dollar weakened against most other currencies.
   ---
   Crude oil prices fell to their lowest level in 18 months
as signs of a drop in OPEC output largely failed to affect a
market plagued by oversupply.
   ---
   Tele-Communications Inc. proposed that its cable systems
become NBC affiliates in rural areas that aren't served by
broadcasters.
   ---
   Donald Trump's bankers reported no progress in bailout
talks. Dozens of Japanese creditors are unwilling to help the
developer and casino owner.
   ---
   Motorola is expected to unveil plans next week for a
satellite communications system that may handle cellular
phone calls in a few years.
   ---
   Ames Department Stores posted a $429.1 million quarterly
loss, possibly signaling more store closings. The firm's
liabilities now exceed its assets.
   ---
   Japan's economy grew at a 10.4% annual rate in the quarter
that ended in March, as the country's exports jumped.
Government officials tried to play down the increase in
exports.
   ---
   Woolworth plans to open as many as a dozen stores in East
Germany by the end of next year. They would be the first
U.S.-owned general merchandise outlets in that country.
   ---
   American Stock Exchange President Kenneth Leibler is
leaving for a top job at Liberty Financial. He was passed
over last fall when the exchange picked a new chairman.
   ---
   PS New Mexico named two officers to succeed Jerry Geist as
chairman and chief executive, but critics said the new aides
will bring little change to the troubled utility.
   ---
   Goodyear expects to report a second-quarter loss as big as
$10 million. The tire maker plans to dismiss 1,100 people in
a revamping that will result in a $35 million pretax charge.
   ---
   Bell Atlantic agreed to acquire Simborg Systems, a pioneer
in healthcare data-management systems.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 134,930,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2893.56, up 11.38; transportation 1178.83, up 3.10; utilities
208.94, up 0.63.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3417.89, off
5.69.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 131.09, off 0.22;
spot index 131.11, off 0.14.
   Dollar: 153.55 yen, off 0.11; 1.6738 marks, off 0.0020.
</TEXT>
