<HL>
   Business Brief -- H.J. Heinz Co.:
   Quarterly Net Climbed 16%;
   Firm Cites Price Increases
</HL>
<DATE>
06/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   HNZ
</CO>
<IN>
FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   H.J. Heinz Co., citing increased prices of its food
products, reported that fiscal fourth-quarter net income
increased nearly 16% as sales rose about 4%.
   In the quarter ended May 2, net was $135.3 million, or 51
cents a share, compared with $117.2 million, or 44 cents a
share, a year earlier.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sales were $1.69 billion, up from $1.63 billion. Sales
gains of products such as ketchup and tuna were offset by
declines in other products, the company said in Pittsburgh.
   For the year, profit jumped nearly 15% to $504.5 million,
or $1.90 a share, from $440.2 million, or $1.67 a share.
Sales rose nearly 5%, to $6.09 billion from $5.8 billion.
Growth came from both price increases and volume gains,
especially from Heinz's major brands, the company said.
</TEXT>
